body:
Would copying this [change](https://github.com/explosion/murmurhash/pull/27/files) work? That's in a completely separate repo but appears to involve the same original murmurhash3 source that we are using?

https://github.com/explosion/murmurhash/blob/c9210577de709cc000894c726101a4750def5022/murmurhash/MurmurHash3.cpp#L66-L94

FYI @edgchen1
yes, that's correct, it should work.

That's possibly gcc specific though so we probably need a more general purpose compile time solution that is hopefully simpler than https://gist.github.com/jtbr/7a43e6281e6cca353b33ee501421860c#file-endianness-h-L31-L65

Possibly this could work: https://stackoverflow.com/a/56348016

As in this file include/onnxruntime/core/framework/endian.h, only platform where macro __BYTE_ORDER__ is not available is WIN32, so having a check as in https://github.com/explosion/murmurhash/blob/c9210577de709cc000894c726101a4750def5022/murmurhash/MurmurHash3.cpp#L66-L94 should work.

issue.body:
**Description**: 
Add big endian handling to the murmurhash3 implementation.

**Motivation and Context**
Address #12504

body: @tvkai As you're building from source would you be able to test out the change in #12549 to validate it works? I don't have a big-endian machine to do able to do so.
@skottmckay Change #12549 is a runtime check and should work for even any future big endian systems that may get added. Fix works on AIX.
The constexpr should mean only one branch is possible at compile time and the dead branch is easily thrown away, so I don't expect there to be any runtime overhead of an endian-ness check.
